<chapter id="prophets" semantic="Introduction to the Prophets">
<cs><img type="csorn" src="csorn.jpg"/><xref idref="rprophets">Introduction to</xref><img type="csorn" src="csorn.jpg"/></cs>
<ctfm><xref idref="rprophets">The Prophets</xref></ctfm>
<figure>
<fig><img type="ctornbottom" src="ctornbottom.jpg"/></fig>
</figure>
<pf>The writing prophets of the OT fall into two groups: the 4 major prophets—Isaiah, Jeremiah, Ezekiel, and Daniel—and the 12 minor prophets—Hosea, Joel, Amos, Obadiah, Jonah, Micah, Nahum, Habakkuk, Zephaniah, Haggai, Zechariah, and Malachi. Lamentations falls into the major-prophet grouping because of its connection with Jeremiah.</pf>
<p>Besides these, the OT regarded others as prophets. Such prophets as Gad, Nathan, Elijah, and Elisha were typical of the nonwriting prophets. In a sense, John the Baptist as a forerunner of Jesus was a prophet who belonged to the OT era.</p>
